ar()" except<br />possibly for arrays or structures that gcc can complain about.<br /><br />It's a horrible thing to use, in that it adds extra cruft to the<br />source code, and then shuts up a compiler warning (even the _reliable_<br />warnings from gcc).<br /><br />It's much better to just initialize the variable, and if gcc some day<br />gets smarter and sees that it  is unnecessary and always overwritten,<br />so much the better. The cost of initializing a single word is<br />basically zero.<br /><br />            Linus<br /><br /></pre><div align="center"><div class="shariff" data-services="[&quot;reddit&quot;]" data-theme="grey" data-lang="en" data-backend-url="//shariff.lkml.org/index.php"></div></div></td><td width="32" rowspan="2" class="c" valign="top"><img src="/images/icornerr.gif" width="32" height="32" alt="\" /></td></tr><tr><td align="right" valign="bottom">
